properties.blog_post:
The section of the Blue Ridge Parkway trail from Soco Gap to Waterrock Knob makes for a steady, invigorating morning hike. The route begins around 4,340 feet and climbs nearly 1,700 feet over roughly six miles, following a narrow ridgeline that transitions from mixed hardwood forest to high-elevation spruce-fir.

In the early morning, the trail is damp and shaded. Ferns, moss, and slick roots line the path, and visibility can shift quickly as low clouds move through trees. The first few miles are mostly uphill with several switchbacks, and the air is very cool today. At higher elevation, red spruce and Fraser fir replace oaks and maples, and I caught glimpses of the Smoky Mountains to the west.
properties.name: MST: Soco Gap to Waterrock Knob

properties.blog_post: There's not much luck in escaping the Nevada heat in April. But here we are. It was a fairly level trail and was a ton of fun because we had some of my wife's family who hiked with us while visiting Las Vegas last year. You can beat the rough temperatures by heading out earlier in the morning which is fortunately what we did. Lots of cyclists rode the main route from The Strip to the trailhead making it fun to see them out on the horizon.
properties.name: North Oak Creek Trail

properties.blog_post: The Mineral Belt is a loop that circumnavigates the city of Leadville, CO. I saw many cross country skiers out on the trail and we were visiting the weekend of the ski joring festival which made for some fun photography. Leadville's founding was largely due to gold and the lead mineral, cerussite which were mined extensively until molybdenum became the primary export. Molybdenum is a rare earth mineral used in silicon chip manufacture and is now mined at many sites around the city. The loop is quite long and isolating in areas but offers a phenomenal moment to trek and see the city and mountains from all sides.
properties.name: Mineral Belt Loop Trail

Koomer Ridge
properties.blog_post: This was a beautiful day in the park. It rained a one or two nights earlier, giving rise to many different kinds of mushrooms and blooming flowers close to the forest floor. The humidity was moderate and the temperature never reached a point where it was noticeably more strenuous throughout the afternoon.

properties.blog_post: This was a balanced trail with snowshoes. Had some beautiful views from creekside.

properties.name: Graenidalur Loop
properties.blog_post:
The Reykjadalur Valley is an active geothermal area and they are famous for the hot spring river. It took us through fantastic nature with a lot of different colors and great views. The water is boiling out of dozens of hot springs in the hills trickle into one body, which is also fed with glacier and rainwater. The results of this is a warm and gentle stream. 

Dad and I thoroughly enjoyed this trail despite the multiple creek crossings and locating the trail half the time on the return journey. This was due to the tall grasses and also losing daylight.
